      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Is the way the internet exposes us to the reality of creators a good or a bad thing? Are we, for example, better for knowing that the creator of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Dilbert",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " is something of a right-wing nut-job? The popular comic strip, which satirised office life in a safe enough way that some companies ‚Äî including one of my former employers ‚Äî felt comfortable embedding it on their intranet, has been ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "yanked from a bunch of newspapers",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/26/us/dilbert-newspapers-racism.html",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", after its creator went on what sounds very much like a racist rant:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Hundreds of newspapers across the country will stop running the ‚ÄúDilbert‚Äù comic strip after its creator said on a YouTube livestream that Black people were ‚Äúa hate group‚Äù and that white people should ‚Äújust get the hell away‚Äù from them.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "quote",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Honestly, I haven‚Äôt paid attention to ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Dilbert",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " for something like 20 years, but the news has created a market for some interesting writing on the subject of the strip and its strengths and weaknesses:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
